Concentrations of radionuclides, CR (mg/m3) are essentially conservative in a chemical sense, but they decay by falling apart in other nuclides and various types of radiation. The radioactive decay rateRate (mg/m3/day) is usually modeled as a first-order process involving a kinetic radioactive decay constant, kdec (1/day). This kinetic constant is derived from the half-life time of the radionuclide. The initial concentration may be expressed as radioactivity, in order to simulate the activity instead of the concentration. These state variablesState variable can be converted into each other using10.58Ac=10-3NAkdecCR/86400Mw,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
